hristopher Stern: [[Creative director|creative direction]]\n* Wayne Barrow (ByStorm Entertainment): management\n* Ambrose \"Pop\" Inman (Cheqmate Management): management\n\n==Chart positions==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (2003)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]\n|align=\"center\"|6\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Top R&B/Hip Hop Albums\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Loon (rapper) albums]]\n[[Category:2003 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Bad Boy Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Scott Storch]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Ryan Leslie]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Buckwild]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Bink (record producer)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Loon\n| type       = Album\n| artist     = [[Loon (rapper)|Loon]]\n| cover      = Loon album.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 21, 2003\n| recorded   = 2001&ndash;2003\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| length     = {{duration|m=60|s=11}}\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Bad Boy Records|Bad Boy]]|[[Universal Records|Universal]]}}\n| producer   = [[Bink (record producer)|Bink!]], [[P. Diddy]] & [[Harve Pierre]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[No Friends]]\n| next_year  = 2006\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Loon\n | type        = [[Album]]\n | single1     = Down for Me\n | single1date = 2003\n | single2     = How You Want That\n | single2date = 2003\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Loon''''' is the first album by American rapper [[Loon (rapper)|Loon]]. It was released on October 21, 2003, through [[Bad Boy Records]] and was produced by [[Sean Combs]], [[Bink (record producer)|Roosevelt \"Bink\" Harrell]], [[Scott Storch]], [[Mario Winans]] and Loon. The album was a success, peaking at number 6 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and number 2 on the [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] chart. \"Down for Me\", the single taken from the album, peaked at number 28 on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Singles & Tracks]] and number 19 on the [[Hot Rap Tracks]].\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=mw0000319086|pure_url=yes}}|title=Loon - ''Loon''|last=Birchmeier|first=Jason|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev2      = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/loon/albums/album/289750/review/6067681/loon|title=Loon: ''Loon''|last=Caramanica|first=Jon|authorlink=Jon Caramanica|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]]|date=November 27, 2003|accessdate=July 10, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070518205122/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/loon/albums/album/289750/review/6067681/loon|archivedate=May 18, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\n[[AllMusic]]'s Jason Birchmeier found the album overlong with its romantic hip-hop tracklist but gave credit to the production for being \"always fresh, lively, and above all, poppy\" concluding that Loon's debut \"overall should please long time [[Bad Boy Records|Bad Boy]] fans and anyone who relishes the label's refined style of lovers rap.\"<ref name=\"AM\"/> [[Jon Caramanica]] from ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' criticized Loon's delivery for lacking variations in technique and lyrical content, and said that the deviation from R&B into \"moral-laden narratives (\"Story\" and \"Don't Wanna Die\")\" or \"joke-poking (\"This Ain't Funny\")\" is where his seduction works the most.<ref name=\"RS\"/>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| title1          = P. Diddy Intro \n| extra1          = Anthony \"Scoe\" Walker\n| length1         = 0:47\n| title2          = How You Want That\n| note2           = Feat. [[Kelis]]\n| extra2          = Yogi\n| length2         = 4:25\n| title3          = Do What You Like\n| note3           = Feat. [[Trina]]\n| extra3          = Yogi\n| length3         = 3:23\n| title4          = Relax Your Mind\n| extra4          = [[Younglord]] & [[Ryan Leslie]]\n| length4         = 4:17\n| title5          = Down For Me\n| note5           = Feat. [[Mario Winans]]\n| extra5          = P. Diddy & Ryan Leslie\n| length5         = 4:19\n| title6          = Barbershop (Interlude)\n| note6           = \n| extra6          = \n| length6         = 1:15\n| title7          = This Ain't Funny\n| extra7          = [[Poke & Tone]]\n| length7         = 3:28\n| title8          = Story\n| extra8          = The Natural aka D-Nat\n| length8         = 3:16\n| title9          = Between Us\n| note9           = Feat. Tammy\n| extra9          = Shaft\n| length9         = 4:47\n| title10         = Like a Movie\n| note10          = Feat. [[Claudette Ortiz]] of [[City High]]\n| extra10         = Akon\n| length10        = 4:14\n| title11         = Pimpin' Ken (Interlude)\n| note11          = \n| extra11         = \n| length11        = 1:40\n| title12         = Hey Woo\n| note12          = Feat. [[Missy Elliott]]\n| extra12         = [[Bink!]]\n| length12        = 3:37\n| title13         = Can't Talk To Her\n| note13          = Feat. [[P. Diddy]] & [[Harve Pierre|Joe Hooker]]\n| extra13         = [[Fredwreck]]\n| length13        = 5:22\n| title14         = Things You Do\n| note14          = Feat.  [[Aaron Hall (singer)|Aaron Hall]]\n| extra14         = Mario Winans\n| length14        = 4:06\n| title15         = Don't Wanna Die\n| note15          = \n| extra15         = [[Younglord]]\n| length15        = 4:28\n| title16         = Waiting\n| note16          = Feat. The Letter M\n| extra16         = [[7 Aurelius]]\n| length16        = 3:46\n| title17         = You Don't Know\n| note17          = \n| extra17         = [[Scott Storch]]\n| length17        = 4:19\n| title18         = Friday Night\n| note18          = \n| extra18         = Yogi\n| length18        = 4:00\n| title19         = I'll Be There\n| note19          = Feat. [[Carl Thomas (singer)|Carl Thomas]]\n| extra19         = Buckwild\n| length19        = 5:21\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nAdapted credits from the album's booklet.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Loon|others=Loon|publisher=Bad Boy|year=2003|type=booklet|id=B000089202}}</ref>\n* Sean \"P.Diddy\" Combs: executive producer\n* Harve Pierre: [[A&R]], executive producer\n* Chris Athens: [[Audio mastering|mastering]] <small>([[Sterling Sound]])</small>\n* Erik Sorensen: additional Pro Tools engineering\n* [[Mark Pitts]]: associate executive producer <small>([[ByStorm Entertainment]])</small>\n* Conrad \"Rad\" Dimanche: A&R\n* Gwendolyn Niles: [[project manager]]\n* Christopher Stern: [[Creative director|creative direction]]\n* Wayne Barrow (ByStorm Entertainment): management\n* Ambrose \"Pop\" Inman (Cheqmate Management): management\n\n==Chart positions==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (2003)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]\n|align=\"center\"|6\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Top R&B/Hip Hop Albums\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Loon (rapper) albums]]\n[[Category:2003 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Bad Boy Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Scott Storch]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Ryan Leslie]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Buckwild]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Bink (record producer)]]\n", "name_user": "DepressedPer", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCritical reception:C/E.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Loon_(album)"}
{"title_page": "Robert Roberts (American politician)", "text_new": "{{Short description|Mayor of Burlington, Vermont}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Robert Roberts\n|image         = Robert Roberts (mayor of Burlington, Vermont).jpg\n|caption       = From 1894's ''Encyclopedia of Vermont Biography''\n|office1       = [[List of mayors of Burlington, Vermont|Mayor]] of [[Burlington, Vermont]]\n|term_start1   = 1911\n|term_end1     = 1913\n|predecessor1  = [[James Edmund Burke]]\n|successor1     = James Edmund Burke\n|term_start2   = 1899\n|term_end2     = 1901\n|predecessor2  = [[Elliot M. Sutton]]\n|successor2    = D. C. Hawley\n|office3       = Member of the [[Vermont Senate]] from [[Chittenden County, Vermont|Chittenden County]]\n|term_start3   = 1890\n|term_end3     = 1892\n|alongside3    = Henry H. Rankin, Isaiah Dow\n|predecessor3  = Elihu B. Taft, Londus F. Terrill, W. Wallace Higbee\n|successor3    = [[David J. Foster]], Samuel A. Brownell, Henry C. Gleason\n|office4       = Member of the [[Vermont House of Representatives]] from Burlington\n|term_start4   = 1882\n|term_end4     = 1884\n|predecessor4  = [[Russell S. Taft]]\n|successor4    = Curtis Ahira Hibbard\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1848|01|01}}\n|birth_place   = [[Manchester, Vermont]]\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1939|02|23|1848|01|01}}\n|death_place   = [[Burlington, Vermont]]\n|party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|resting_place = [[Lakeview Cemetery (Burlington, Vermont)|Lakeview Cemetery]], Burlington, Vermont\n|spouse        = Minnie Elizabeth Lyman (m. 1886-1939, his death)\n|education     = [[University of Vermont]]\n|profession    = Attorney\n}}\n\n'''Robert Roberts''' (January 1, 1848 - February 23, 1939) was an American attorney and politician from Vermont. Among the offices he held, Roberts was twice [[list of mayors of Burlington, Vermont|mayor of Burlington]], first from 1899 to 1901, and again from 1911 to 1913.\n\n==Early life==\nRobert Roberts was born in [[Manchester, Vermont]] on January 1, 1848, a son of Daniel Roberts and Caroline Diantha (Martindale) Roberts.{{sfn|Dodge}}{{sfn|\"Robert Roberts, Former Mayor, Dies at 91\"}} He attended [[Burlington High School (Vermont)|Burlington High School]] in [[Burlington, Vermont|Burlington]] and Manchester's [[Burr and Burton Academy|Burr and Burton Seminary]], then began attendance at the [[University of Vermont]].{{sfn|Dodge}} While in college, Roberts joined the [[Delta Psi (University of Vermont)|Delta Psi]] fraternity and [[Phi Beta Kappa]].{{sfn|Dodge}} After graduating in 1869, Roberts attended [[Columbia Law School]] for a year, then continued his studies in [[French language|French]] at schools in [[Paris]] and [[Geneva]].{{sfn|Dodge}}{{sfn|\"Robert Roberts, Former Mayor, Dies at 91\"}} While studying in Europe, Roberts was a correspondent for several newspapers in the United States.{{sfn|Dodge}}\n\n==Legal career==\nRoberts was [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admitted to the bar]] in 1871 and began to practice in Burlington.{{sfn|Dodge}} A [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], Roberts began a career in politics and government when he was appointed reporter for the [[Vermont Senate]]'s sessions of 1874, 1878 and 1880.{{sfn|Dodge}}\n\nIn 1876 and 1877, Roberts practiced law in [[Chicago]].{{sfn|Dodge}} He then resumed residence in Burlington, where he practiced law in partnership with his father.{{sfn|Dodge}} They maintained the firm of Roberts & Roberts until Daniel Roberts died in 1899, after which Robert Roberts practiced alone.{{sfn|Dodge}}\n\nRoberts was a member of the Merchants National Bank board of directors, the University of Vermont board if trustees, and the board of trustees of the Vermont State Library.{{sfn|Dodge}} In 1910, he compiled and published the ''Vermont Digest'', a reference work on the decisions of the [[Vermont Supreme Court]].{{sfn|Dodge}} In compiling this work, Roberts revised 60 volumes of decisions that had previously been compiled by his father, and updated it to 82 volumes.{{sfn|\"Robert Roberts, Former Mayor, Dies at 91\"}} Roberts's civic and professional memberships included the [[Vermont Bar Association]], Ethan Allen Club, Algonquin Club, [[Sons of the American Revolution]] and Waubanakee Golf Club.{{sfn|Dodge}}\n\n==Political career==\nFrom 1882 to 1884, Roberts represented Burlington in the [[Vermont House of Representatives]].{{sfn|Dodge}} While in the House, Roberts was a member of the judiciary committee and chairman of the committee on revised bills.{{sfn|Dodge}} From 1887 to 1889, he was Burlington's city attorney.{{sfn|Dodge}} \n\nFrom 1890 to 1892, Roberts represented [[Chittenden County, Vermont|Chittenden County]] in the [[Vermont Senate]].{{sfn|Dodge}} During his Senate term, Roberts was chairman of the judiciary committee.{{sfn|Dodge}}\n\nIn 1899 and 1900, Roberts won election as [[list of mayors of Burlington, Vermont|mayor of Burlington]], and he served from April 1899 to April 1901.{{sfn|Dodge}} In 1911, he was again elected mayor, and he served until 1913.{{sfn|Dodge}}\n\n==Death and burial==\nRoberts died at his home in Burlington on February 23, 1939.{{sfn|\"Robert Roberts, Former Mayor, Dies at 91\"}} For several years before his death, Roberts was the University of Vermont's oldest living graduate.{{sfn|\"Robert Roberts, Former Mayor, Dies at 91\"}} Roberts's funeral took place at the Congregational church on College Street, and honorary pallbearers included [[Guy W. Bailey]], [[Harland B. Howe]], [[James Edmund Burke]], [[Clarence H. Beecher]], and [[John Holmes Jackson]].{{sfn|\"City and U.V.M. Pay Final Tribute to Robert Roberts\"}} Roberts was buried at [[Lakeview Cemetery (Burlington, Vermont)|Lakeview Cemetery]] in Burlington.{{sfn|\"City and U.V.M. Pay Final Tribute to Robert Roberts\"}}\n\n==Family==\nIn 1886, Roberts married Minnie Elizabeth Lyman (1861-1940).{{sfn|Dodge}} They were married until his death, and had no children.{{sfn|\"Robert Roberts, Former Mayor, Dies at 91\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n===Books===\n*{{cite book |last=Dodge |first=Prentiss Cutler |date=1912 |title=Encyclopedia of Vermont Biography |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tt2_3hTQxFMC&pg=PA301 |location=Burlington, VT |publisher=Ullery Publishing Company |pages=301-302 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|Dodge}}}}\n\n===Newspapers===\n*{{cite news |date=February 23, 1939 |title=Robert Roberts, Former Mayor, Dies at 91 |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48645195/robert-roberts-dies/ |work=[[Burlington Free Press]] |location=Burlington, VT |page=15 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Robert Roberts, Former Mayor, Dies at 91\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=February 27, 1939 |title=City and U.V.M. Pay Final Tribute to Robert Roberts |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48645906/final-tribute/ |work=[[Burlington Free Press]] |location=Burlington, VT |page=7 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"City and U.V.M. Pay Final Tribute to Robert Roberts\"}}}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Findagrave|33138956}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roberts, Robert.}}\n[[Category:1848 births]]\n[[Category:1939 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Manchester, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Burlington, Vermont]]\n[[Category:University of Vermont alumni]]\n[[Category:Vermont lawyers]]\n[[Category:Vermont Republicans]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Burlington, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Members of the Vermont House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Vermont state senators]]\n[[Category:Burials at Lakeview Cemetery (Burlington, Vermont)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Mayor of Burlington, Vermont}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Robert Roberts\n|image         = Robert Roberts (mayor of Burlington, Vermont).jpg\n|caption       = From 1894's ''Encyclopedia of Vermont Biography''\n|office1       = [[List of mayors of Burlington, Vermont|Mayor]] of [[Burlington, Vermont]]\n|term_start1   = 1911\n|term_end1     = 1913\n|predecessor1  = [[James Edmund Burke]]\n|successor1     = James Edmund Burke\n|term_start2   = 1899\n|term_end2     = 1901\n|predecessor2  = [[Elliot M. Sutton]]\n|successor2    = D. C. Hawley\n|office3       = Member of the [[Vermont Senate]] from [[Chittenden County, Vermont|Chittenden County]]\n|term_start3   = 1890\n|term_end3     = 1892\n|alongside3    = Henry H. Rankin, Isaiah Dow\n|predecessor3  = Elihu B. Taft, Londus F. Terrill, W. Wallace Higbee\n|successor3    = [[David J. Foster]], Samuel A. Brownell, Henry C. Gleason\n|office4       = Member of the [[Vermont House of Representatives]] from Burlington\n|term_start4   = 1882\n|term_end4     = 1884\n|predecessor4  = [[Russell S. Taft]]\n|successor4    = Curtis Ahira Hibbard\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1848|01|01}}\n|birth_place   = [[Manchester, Vermont]]\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1939|02|23|1848|01|01}}\n|death_place   = [[Burlington, Vermont]]\n|party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|resting_place = [[Lakeview Cemetery (Burlington, Vermont)|Lakeview Cemetery]], Burlington, Vermont\n|spouse        = Minnie Elizabeth Lyman (m. 1886-1939, his death)\n|education     = [[University of Vermont]]\n|profession    = Attorney\n}}\n\n'''Robert Roberts''' (January 1, 1848 - February 23, 1939) was an American attorney and politician from Vermont. Among the offices he held, Roberts was twice [[list of mayors of Burlington, Vermont|mayor of Burlington]], first from 1899 to 1901, and again from 1911 to 1913.\n\n==Early life==\nRobert Roberts was born in [[Manchester, Vermont]] on January 1, 1848, a son of Daniel Roberts and Caroline Diantha (Martindale) Roberts.{{sfn|Dodge}}{{sfn|\"Robert Roberts, Former Mayor, Dies at 91\"}} He attended [[Burlington High School (Vermont)|Burlington High School]] in [[Burlington, Vermont|Burlington]] and Manchester's [[Burr and Burton Academy|Burr and Burton Seminary]], then began attendance at the [[University of Vermont]].{{sfn|Dodge}} While in college, Roberts joined the [[Delta Psi (University of Vermont)|Delta Psi]] fraternity and [[Phi Beta Kappa]].{{sfn|Dodge}} After graduating in 1869, Roberts attended [[Columbia Law School]] for a year, then continued his studies in [[French language|French]] at schools in [[Paris]] and [[Geneva]].{{sfn|Dodge}}{{sfn|\"Robert Roberts, Former Mayor, Dies at 91\"}} While studying in Europe, Roberts was a correspondent for several newspapers in the United States.{{sfn|Dodge}}\n\n==Legal career==\nRoberts was [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admitted to the bar]] in 1871 and began to practice in Burlington.{{sfn|Dodge}} A [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], Roberts began a career in politics and government when he was appointed reporter for the [[Vermont Senate]]'s sessions of 1874, 1878 and 1880.{{sfn|Dodge}}\n\nIn 1876 and 1877, Roberts practiced law in [[Chicago]].{{sfn|Dodge}} He then resumed residence in Burlington, where he practiced law in partnership with his father.{{sfn|Dodge}} They maintained the firm of Roberts & Roberts until Daniel Roberts died in 1899, after which Robert Roberts practiced alone.{{sfn|Dodge}}\n\nRoberts was a member of the Merchants National Bank board of directors, the University of Vermont board if trustees, and the board of trustees of the Vermont State Library.{{sfn|Dodge}} In 1910, he compiled and published the ''Vermont Digest'', a reference work on the decisions of the [[Vermont Supreme Court]].{{sfn|Dodge}} In compiling this work, Roberts revised 60 volumes of decisions that had been compiled by his father, and updated it to 82 volumes.{{sfn|\"Robert Roberts, Former Mayor, Dies at 91\"}} Roberts's civic and professional memberships included the [[Vermont Bar Association]], Ethan Allen Club, Algonquin Club, [[Sons of the American Revolution]] and Waubanakee Golf Club.{{sfn|Dodge}}\n\n==Political career==\nFrom 1882 to 1884, Roberts represented Burlington in the [[Vermont House of Representatives]].{{sfn|Dodge}} While in the House, Roberts was a member of the judiciary committee and chairman of the committee on revised bills.{{sfn|Dodge}} From 1887 to 1889, he was Burlington's city attorney.{{sfn|Dodge}} \n\nFrom 1890 to 1892, Roberts represented [[Chittenden County, Vermont|Chittenden County]] in the [[Vermont Senate]].{{sfn|Dodge}} During his Senate term, Roberts was chairman of the judiciary committee.{{sfn|Dodge}}\n\nIn 1899 and 1900, Roberts won election as [[list of mayors of Burlington, Vermont|mayor of Burlington]], and he served from April 1899 to April 1901.{{sfn|Dodge}} In 1911, he was again elected mayor, and he served until 1913.{{sfn|Dodge}}\n\n==Death and burial==\nRoberts died at his home in Burlington on February 23, 1939.{{sfn|\"Robert Roberts, Former Mayor, Dies at 91\"}} For several years before his death, Roberts was the University of Vermont's oldest living graduate.{{sfn|\"Robert Roberts, Former Mayor, Dies at 91\"}} Roberts's funeral took place at the Congregational church on College Street, and honorary pallbearers included [[Guy W. Bailey]], [[Harland B. Howe]], [[James Edmund Burke]], [[Clarence H. Beecher]], and [[John Holmes Jackson]].{{sfn|\"City and U.V.M. Pay Final Tribute to Robert Roberts\"}} Roberts was buried at [[Lakeview Cemetery (Burlington, Vermont)|Lakeview Cemetery]] in Burlington.{{sfn|\"City and U.V.M. Pay Final Tribute to Robert Roberts\"}}\n\n==Family==\nIn 1886, Roberts married Minnie Elizabeth Lyman (1861-1940).{{sfn|Dodge}} They were married until his death, and had no children.{{sfn|\"Robert Roberts, Former Mayor, Dies at 91\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n===Books===\n*{{cite book |last=Dodge |first=Prentiss Cutler |date=1912 |title=Encyclopedia of Vermont Biography |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tt2_3hTQxFMC&pg=PA301 |location=Burlington, VT |publisher=Ullery Publishing Company |pages=301-302 |via=[[Google Books]